        </m:math>
      </para>
      <para id="import-auto-id597162">Since one mole contains a fixed number of particles, regardless of the type of particle, calculating the number of moles <emphasis effect="italics">n</emphasis> is a way of counting the number of particles in a sample with mass <emphasis effect="italics">m</emphasis>.  For example, in the 100.0 g sample of the compound above, we have 40.0 g of carbon, 53.3 g of oxygen, and 6.7 g of hydrogen.  We can calculate the number of moles of atoms of each element using the equation above:</para>
