      <para id="import-auto-id514387">This means we have counted the number of particles of CH<sub>4</sub> in our sample.  And we know that the number of particles of CO<sub>2</sub> produced must be the same as this, because the chemical equation shows us the 1:1 ratio of CH<sub>4</sub> to CO<sub>2</sub>.  So, 62.5 moles of CO<sub>2</sub> are produced by this reaction and this 1.0 kg sample.</para>
      <para id="import-auto-id589147">We are usually more interested in the mass of the product, and we can calculate this, too.  The mass of one mole of CO<sub>2</sub> is found from the mass of one mole of C and two moles of O, and is therefore 44.0 g.  This is the mass for one mole.  The mass for 62.5 moles will be</para>
